x4freetext: Proton beams with E=500-2200 keV at McMaster U.,
E=300-900 keV at U. Toronto, E=80-350 keV at U. Munster
and E=700-2200 keV at U. Stuttgart.
40 cm3 and 80 cm3 detectors.
Targets were produced by heating
0.25 mm thick tungsten sheets to a dull red in oxygen
gas. In addition, Ta2O5 targets were produced by
anodizing 0.1 mm thick Ta sheets in 99% 18O enriched
water.
The beam passed through a 1.5 cm diameter Ta
collimator and was focused into a profile of 1.5 cm
diameter on the target. For the measurements of
excitation functions at Ep=80-350 keV, the 80 cm3
Ge(Li) detector was positioned at 0 degrees in close
geometry (1.4 cm distance between the front face of the
crystal and the target). For subsequent investigations
in this energy range as well as all other experiments
at higher beam energies, the targets were mounted at 45
degrees to the beam direction. Due to the higher
capture cross sections at the higher beam energies no
lead shielding was necessary. In the study of
excitation functions and resonance properties at
Ep > 300 keV, the Ge(Li) detector was placed-at 45
degrees  in close geometry. In the study of gamma-ray
angular distributions, gamma-ray spectra were obtained
at theta = O, 45 and   90 degrees with the Ge(Li)
detector at a distance of d = 7 cm from the target.
An additional Ge(Li) detector at theta=-90 degrees
was used as a monitor.
At each point in the measurement of the
excitation functions, all primary and secondary gamma-
ray transitions observed in the Ge(Li) spectra were
used in the analyses. Due to the steep drop in the
reaction cross section at low bombarding energies,
only the secondary transitions from the very
low-lying states in 19F were observed at these beam
energies. The excitation energies of all states have
been deduced from the energies of de-excitation
gamma-rays). These values were then used in
conjunction with the Q-value) to determine the proton
resonance energies. The excitation energies, obtained
in the present work, were used throughout this work
as nomenclature for referring to the states. The
total widths (or upper limits) were determined from
the yield curves. For the narrow resonances, the
slope of the leading edge of a thick target yield
curve was used in a calculation incorporating both
the characteristic shape of a resonance known to be
very narrow and the energy dependence of the
resolution function of the beam.
